	<h3 class="piece_header"> <%= @title2 %> </h3>
	<p>
— there she was, staring at me<br>
<br>
I heard her voice first.<br>
<br>
“That’s the wrong direction.”<br>

Then I turned around and there she was, staring at me, with a half-smile and her fingers wrapped tight around a phone.<br>
<br>
“Uh, I need a ride. My truck…” I took a step forward, but she edged back.<br>
<br>
She must’ve been afraid. It made sense; after all, she was a young girl — 15, 16 maybe — all alone in the Mojave, hiking towards Coachella. I’m not sure where she came from, or how she snuck up on me. She must’ve been walking for a while.<br>
<br>
“That’s the wrong direction,” she repeated, interrupting my musings. She pointed a single skinny finger towards the horizon. “You need to go that way.”<br>
<br>
Her voice was soft and lilting, but her eyes held another message altogether, intruding upon my own thoughts with a dialogue all her own.<br>
<br>
I’m not sure why I didn’t think to ask her what she was doing here, on Highway 61 ninety miles from everywhere. Alone. I remembered seeing a “Next Services” sign, but that was a long way back, before the rumble and the sputter and the crash, when I woke up to find the wheels stuck in the sand and the Toyota dented. I had unstrapped my seat belt, grabbed my map, and took to the road.<br>
<br>
The wrong direction — she repeated, but this time, her lips did not move.
<br> <br>
I didn’t answer. How could I? There was something about her tone that dictated a response was not necessary. And she was giving me the creeps.
<br> <br>
Besides, she didn’t need an answer. I could feel it and I knew, I just knew: her matter-of-fact statement — -“the wrong direction” — was some kind of command to be obeyed. Even though she was at least ten years my junior, and alone on the desert with only a phone.
<br> <br>
My eyes drifted downwards, to her million-year-old cell phone. I hadn’t seen one like it in years. It may have even been an original, sought by some collector on E-bay. Except hers was scuffed-up, very much used.
<br> <br>
“Are you getting any service out here?” I asked.
<br> <br>
“No.” This time she spoke. Her voice was little more than a whisper, as if it hurt her to speak. She glanced at the long stretch of road over my shoulder and reissued her request. “Don’t go in that direction.”
<br> <br>
“But my car is that way.” I pointed towards my Toyota, more for myself than for her. “And I need help.”
<br> <br>
She didn’t answer me. She was definitely making me nervous.
<br> <br>
I ignored the feeling, and, instead, knelt down on my knees and opened up the map. There must be a little town, or a little gas station somewhere.
<br> <br>
I looked up to ask the girl, after all, she would know, she came from somewhere. I was prepared to see her eyes, watchful, steady, and her lips, slightly open, as if ready to speak.
<br> <br>
But she was gone. There was only a sea of beige in all directions, and no girl.
<br> <br>
I was too thirsty, too tired. I stood up and rubbed my eyes. I needed to find help. So, I began to walk. I didn’t listen to the girl. I didn’t change directions. There was no way I was going back.
<br> <br>
Hell no! I’ve already gone this far — In my mind, I swore at the girl, whose voice was now in my head — Turn around — she whispered.
<br> <br>
I pressed on, ignoring her, dragging my feet across the asphalt.
<br> <br>
Turn around — Her words reverberated, over and over. After a while, I couldn’t tell if it was her voice I was hearing, or mine.
<br> <br>
I think it was an hour later that I caught sight of a vehicle parked by the side of the road. I accelerated my pace. The sun was high overhead and burning down by the time I reached it. I was surprised to find it was a Toyota, like mine. Dusty and deserted. It was even the same shade of blue, with a dent in the rear. And it was also stuck in the sand.
<br> <br>
Yet mine was a day’s walk in the other direction. At least I thought it was the other direction.
<br> <br>
Hot and exhausted, I climbed in, not ready to argue with the logic of what appears to be and what is. The upholstery was warm to the touch, and beside me was a bottle of water, still full. I grabbed it eagerly, pressing my parched lips against the plastic. My throat was nearly swollen with thirst and I was eager to taste the cool liquid as it slid down my throat. I thought of the girl walking around out there, alone. Maybe even thirsty.
<br> <br>
In my memory, I heard her words — you need to go the other way. Then I realized the water wasn’t coming out. I was thirstier than ever.
<br> <br>
Across from me, the door to the Toyota began to open wide.
<br> <br>
“Yeah, there is.” The tan sleeve of a California Highway Patrol officer appeared first, followed by a wrinkled face as the man peered into the cab of the Toyota. He let go of the door and I watched as he pressed two fingers against a dark heap slumped beside me. I hadn’t noticed it before.
<br> <br>
“Hey! I’m glad to see you! I need water. My truck, it crashed…” My words tumbled out dry and raspy, but the officer ignored me.
<br> <br>
“What’s the status?” A deeper voice came from behind the officer.
<br> <br>
“No pulse.” Answered the officer closer to me, “Looks like she died on impact.”
<br> <br>
“Hey!” I waved at him, but he was too busy with the pile, which, looking closer, I could see she was actually a woman collapsed against the steering wheel. She was about my age and my height and my weight. She even had brown hair, like mine, speckled with grey. She obviously needed some help.
<br> <br>
“Yeah — no pulse.” The CHP officer repeated, turning over the motionless form. “I don’t know how, but that girl at the gas station was right.”
<br> <br>
The unconscious heap seemed to roll in protest, her head turning last, her eyes open, wide, staring… There was something about the eyes that I recognized. Something familiar, almost…
<br> <br>
“They gotta do something with this highway…” The voice outside was moving closer, getting louder.
<br> <br>
The woman in the seat beside me did not blink. Her brown eyes stared past me, over my shoulder.
<br> <br>
I looked away, not wanting to look at her, not wanting to hear the highway patrol officer, not wanting to be there. Then, another voice joined the men. I knew the voice, well.
<br> <br>
I squeezed my eyes, tight, hoping to make it go away, hoping to make her go away. but I could still see her, even in behind my closed eyelids. She was standing on the asphalt in front of me –a solitary image on the road that led to endlessness in all directions.
<br> <br>
“You need to go the other way,” she whispered, her words drifting in through the open car window, surrounding me.
<br> <br>
In a moment of panic, hoping it was it was a dream, I flashed my eyes open, but she was still there. She was exactly as I knew she would be — standing on the road in front of me, pointing her same thin finger at the horizon, just as she did before.
<br> <br>
This time her eyes were steady and unflinching. Unavoidable.
<br> <br>
“It’s time to go.”
	</p>
