	<p>
Emma knew that when he arrived she wouldn’t tell him that she had left forty-five minutes early just to make sure she could still find the place. It was a restaurant on the north side of town and it had been ages since she made the journey. And, after all, she reminded herself, he was the one that always did the driving, especially when, well — it’d been a while.
<br> <br> 
Above, the flights flickered. It was a quick off-and-on — a gust of wind, maybe — probably the prelude that signified the storm-to-come. Emma took notice of it, but that was all. It was December and to be expected, really. No one else seemed bothered by it.
<br> <br> 
Her thoughts went back to Greg, driving on the road. Maybe the storm was breaking on the other side of town where Greg worked. Maybe it was the rain slowing him down. Or, perhaps the wind?
<br> <br> 
No, Emma reminded herself, Greg’s lateness was expected. Somewhat. It was one part of what made him, him. A tiny part of the whole that she still loved — dare she admit it? — part of the take-it-all or leave-it-all bundle and, really, it was the only way to really love him.
<br> <br> 
She unfolded her legs and slid her right foot free from the simple, yet elegant black pump. With nyloned-toes, she scratched her left ankle, feeling the sharpness of her big toe nail. Then she remembered —darn it! — she had forgotten to pick up a toenail clipper when she was at Walgreens.
<br> <br> 
Emma continued to run her big toe over her ankle bone, trying to scratch the itch over the knobby, but freckled flesh, all wrapped tight in nude and silky, Sheer Energy Size B, control top.
<br> <br> 
Ah- she remembered, it wouldn’t be long till she could remove them. Either way.
<br> <br> 
Even so, Greg’s lateness was painful. It was gut-wrenching, infuriating, just like had always been. Every notch the minute hand moved forward ignited a brand-new set of issues, concerns, anxieties. Maybe he had second thoughts? Perhaps I misunderstood?
<br> <br> 
Still, it was only a meeting “for drinks,” to remember “old times.”
<br> <br> 
She thought back to the words that arrived, casually, in text-form. From Greg’s phone to hers. Yesterday, at 6:45 p.m. The exact time was important.
<br> <br> 
The third time the hostess appeared, Emma wondered, again, if he had sent the message on accident. Perhaps he confused her with the newest love of his life. Maybe the message was meant for another “E”? Had he dated an “Elizabeth,” an “Eliza,” an “Elsie”? She smiled at the idea of him dating an “Elsie.” Yes, sadly, all of the women she’d seen him with could easily have been called Elsie. He definitely had a type: fluffy-haired, dyed blonde, or red, or black — never naturally so. But always bubbly and thin. Chatty and poodle-like. The appearance changed, slightly, whether fair-skinned or dark, they all shopped at Nordstrom, they all drove some BMW or Lexus and wore spiked-high Stilettos and posted air-brushed portraits of themselves on their Facebook page.
<br> <br> 
Not that Emma checked. Well, not often, at least.
<br> <br> 
But what had she replied to him? Before she could scroll through her messages to find the answer, the girl was in front of her, asking the question, again.
<br> <br> 
Again, Emma forced herself to smile. “No, thank you. I’ll wait.”
<br> <br> 
The girl smiled back. Her smile was only somewhat forced, but friendly. Sort of.
<br> <br> 
“Josie,” her nametag read. She, along with “Susanna,” were the night hostesses. That’s what the waitress had said when she set down the vodka soda with a squirt of cranberry.
<br> <br> 
Don’t worry, you can take your drink with you. I’ll find you when your other half arrives if you escape to a cozy table in the back. Definitely request it, if you know what I mean — then the waitress winked at her, smiling.
<br> <br> 
Politely, Emma smiled back. My other half? He used to be my other half, but not now. Past-tense.
<br> <br> 
She looked back towards the door. So, if the text was not a mistake, then he wants to talk over “old times.” Except, that is precisely what the problem is. Which of the “old times” did he want to discuss?
<br> <br> 
Or re-live.
<br> <br> 
She looked down at her nails: casually neutral. They were a product of a mad-dash lunch time manicure with Suzie, after she knew what she would wear today — a sweater and skirt. Later, on the way here, she stopped at Walgreens and bought a lipstick that would match (but forgot the toenail clipper!) The color was called Forgotten Carmel.
<br> <br> 
Relax — she willed her shoulders, her wrists.
<br> <br> 
Look out the window, at the trees –not the parking lot, not the door. She stretched out her hands, crossing one on top of the other. Casual and neutral. Like her nails.
<br> <br> 
But it wasn’t working.
<br> <br> 
It was twenty-five minutes past the hour when she glanced at the lacquered oak doors. One last time, she told herself. One last time and I’ll look. If he’s not walking through the doors, I’m leaving.
<br> <br> 
But she knew she wouldn’t.
	</p>
