	<p>
Somebody died last night — 
while I slept between cotton, then awakened, briefly, 
my toes brushing across wiry hairs of the chihuahua
buried deep between blanketed folds of down.
<br> <br> 
He snapped at the affront, teeth sharp against my flesh,
rattled, shaken, aware he had been exposed. His anonymity
gone. The moment was over in one-half of one minute,
or maybe it was a Nano-second, or maybe it was exactly the time
it took for the bullet to strike. Fire
<br> <br> 
and a glimmer of light, a burst of heat
and sound. A battle of iron versus bone, a slicing
that severs with molten metal;
<br> <br> 
copper, iron, steel and a steamy
end to eternity,
<br> <br> 
it’s victor to be revealed only after the hours and minutes and seconds
transition forward and the universe bids farewell
to the morning after. Long after the Chihuahua 
has drifted back to sleep.
<br> <br> 
But Somebody died.
<br> <br> 
Many Somebodies. Expelling
life: folding and falling, palms to the heavens, eyes fixed
on the nothingness of everything, under star-cloaked 
darkness and the fluorescent glow of bleached-white 
rooms scrubbed germ-free with Lysol.
<br> <br> 
And she who carried Somebody, the uterus
that nursed her child to an almost-adult adolescence?
If not touching, finger-to-finger, standing vigil, inhaling
each of Somebody’s exhale, did she slumber
<br> <br> 
one block away? Or one hundred or one thousand? cushioned
in-between satin and percale and cotton, dreaming
of tomorrow. Did she hear the whispered thud or thump
<br> <br> 
as her first or last or middle or only
 — her well-beloved sack of progeny DNA — exhaled
a final sigh?
<br> <br> 
Did her eyes flutter open? Sensing
her life’s greatest accomplishment
was evaporating, deflating, because
<br> <br> 
Somebody died last night.
<br> <br> 
Victim, oppressor, hero, savior, defender, antagonist, liar, thief; brave firewalkers all, battling fleshy flames tangled in steel, yet
<br> <br> 
never mind.
<br> <br> 
In a last cleansing of blood and air,
Somebody will live on, initiated
into sainthood in a final outburst of sound and heat and salt-water tears,
trailing along the cheekbones of the living
as flesh-covered comrades and strangers, pulsating
with blood, sinew, cilia and sparks of nerve, remember
<br> <br> 
those who walked through the fire when
Somebody died last night.
